[
    {
        "content": "<p>Hello friends, in the section <a href=\"https://leanprover.github.io/theorem_proving_in_lean4/propositions_and_proofs.html#working-with-propositions-as-types\">Working with Propositions as Types</a>, a proof of <code>p → q → p</code> is given as follows:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">variable</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Prop</span><span class=\"o\">}</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">variable</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">q</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Prop</span><span class=\"o\">}</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">theorem</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">t1</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">→</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">q</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">→</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">fun</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">hp</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">fun</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">hq</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">q</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">hp</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>I was trying to to create a proof for <code>p → q</code> in a similar fashion, but the following does not work</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">example</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">→</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">q</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">fun</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">hp</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">fun</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">hq</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">q</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">hq</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Lean complains that the types don't match, but I am not able to figure out an expression that would make them match.<br>\nWhat am I doing wrong?</p>",
        "id": 479046654,
        "sender_full_name": "Krishna Padmasola",
        "timestamp": 1729945005
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Well, that's because you cannot really prove <code>p -&gt; q</code> for arbitrary propositions <code>p</code>, <code>q</code>.</p>",
        "id": 479047848,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex Mobius",
        "timestamp": 1729946259
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Here, writng an implication as a function would be writing a function to provide a proof of arbitrary <code>q</code> given a proof of arbitrary <code>p</code>. You cannot provide that, because <code>p</code> and <code>q</code> are not really related.<br>\nIn the first example, what you're proving is <code>p -&gt; (q -&gt; p)</code>, i.e. \"given knowledge that <code>p</code> is true, <code>p</code> follows from anything\", which is provable.</p>",
        "id": 479048009,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex Mobius",
        "timestamp": 1729946407
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"767265\">@Alex Mobius</span> that makes sense now.<br>\nAnother thing I'm trying to wrap my head around is <code>Prop</code> vs <code>Bool</code>.<br>\nWhy are there 2 types for the same thing?</p>",
        "id": 479048621,
        "sender_full_name": "Krishna Padmasola",
        "timestamp": 1729947087
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>because for one, you get excluded middle by construction.</p>",
        "id": 479048723,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1729947146
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(sort of)</p>",
        "id": 479048733,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1729947158
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>for example:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">example</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Bool</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">false</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∨</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">true</span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Bool</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">rec</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">Or</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">inl</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">rfl</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">Or</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">inr</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">rfl</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 479048886,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1729947312
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><code>Bool</code> is a truth that's only known a runtime, <code>Prop</code> is a truth that is known at type-checking type. There's a type class called <code>Decidable</code> which bridges the two.<br>\n<code>Prop</code> is a type of many possible types (propositions) that have either 1 or 0 elements - its only element is the proof of the proposition if the proposition is correct. Therefore, the type checker can check if an element of that type can be constructed given known theorems. <code>Bool</code> is a type that has 2 elements, they are also 1 and 0, but they're just numbers with special arithmetic instead of \"amount of proofs\"</p>",
        "id": 479048930,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex Mobius",
        "timestamp": 1729947356
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I hope this makes sense!</p>",
        "id": 479048975,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex Mobius",
        "timestamp": 1729947366
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"684366\">@Edward van de Meent</span> thanks, I think I need to read up on recursors and axiom of choice (?) to have a deeper understanding of your answer.</p>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"767265\">@Alex Mobius</span> type-checking time vs runtime is an interesting observation. Does that mean we cannot create any propositions that involve runtime computation?</p>\n<p>When you say <code>Decidable</code> does the bridging, does that mean we can use <code>Prop</code> in place of <code>Bool</code>, for example in <code>if</code> expressions?</p>\n<p>I tried the following but it did not work</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">def</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">z</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Prop</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">set_option</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">diagnostics</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">true</span>\n<span class=\"bp\">#</span><span class=\"n\">eval</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">if</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">z</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">then</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">10</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">else</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">20</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>I get the error message <code>failed to synthesize  Decidable z</code></p>",
        "id": 479051773,
        "sender_full_name": "Krishna Padmasola",
        "timestamp": 1729950100
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>also tried this, which does not work</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">def</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">z</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Prop</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">theorem</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">zth</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">z</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">rfl</span>\n<span class=\"bp\">#</span><span class=\"n\">check</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">zth</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">set_option</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">diagnostics</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">true</span>\n<span class=\"bp\">#</span><span class=\"n\">eval</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">if</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">zth</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">then</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">10</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">else</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">20</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>but this works, not sure why, because the proof is not supplied</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"bp\">#</span><span class=\"n\">eval</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">if</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">then</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">10</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">else</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">20</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 479053093,
        "sender_full_name": "Krishna Padmasola",
        "timestamp": 1729951379
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><code>failed to synthesize Decidable z</code> means that it couldn't automatically do the bridging.</p>\n<p>The issue is that <code>Decidable</code> synthesis won't unfold definitions unless they are reducible. If you change it to <code>abbrev z</code> it will work, since this marks the definition as being reducible. Definitions are \"semi-reducible\" by default.</p>",
        "id": 479064050,
        "sender_full_name": "Kyle Miller",
        "timestamp": 1729961738
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><code>if zth then 10 else 20</code> is a type error because <code>zth</code> is a proof, not a proposition</p>",
        "id": 479064117,
        "sender_full_name": "Kyle Miller",
        "timestamp": 1729961795
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>thanks <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"306601\">@Kyle Miller</span> so in <code>if 2 = 2 then ...</code> Lean is able to prove that the proposition is true by itself? Is that what is meant by synthesizing <code>Decidable</code>or bridging?</p>",
        "id": 479064895,
        "sender_full_name": "Krishna Padmasola",
        "timestamp": 1729962657
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, it synthesizes a <code>Decidable (2 = 2)</code> instance there</p>",
        "id": 479064912,
        "sender_full_name": "Kyle Miller",
        "timestamp": 1729962678
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Even though <code>Decidable z</code> is definitionally equal to <code>Decidable (2 = 2)</code>, typeclass synthesis won't unfold <code>z</code>. (This is intentional, to let people create type synonym with properties that are different from the old type.)</p>",
        "id": 479064981,
        "sender_full_name": "Kyle Miller",
        "timestamp": 1729962749
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>By the way, <code>Decidable p</code> is pretty much <code>Bool</code>, but its versions of <code>true</code> and <code>false</code> contain either a proof or disproof of <code>p</code>. This is how the bridging is done.</p>",
        "id": 479065017,
        "sender_full_name": "Kyle Miller",
        "timestamp": 1729962817
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If you need to, you would do it like that:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">instance</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Decidable</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">z</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">unfold</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">z</span><span class=\"bp\">;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">infer_impl</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 479065068,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex Mobius",
        "timestamp": 1729962849
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>or <code>instance : Decidable z := inferInstanceAs &lt;| Decidable (2 = 2)</code></p>",
        "id": 479065083,
        "sender_full_name": "Kyle Miller",
        "timestamp": 1729962883
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(do you mean <code>infer_instance</code> <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"767265\">@Alex Mobius</span> ?)</p>",
        "id": 479065128,
        "sender_full_name": "Kyle Miller",
        "timestamp": 1729962927
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Since <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"767265\">@Alex Mobius</span> pointed out in the thread above that we cannot prove <code>p -&gt; q</code> for arbitrary <code>p</code> and <code>q</code> (it makes sense now that I think about it),  I tried to prove for specific <code>p</code> and <code>q</code></p>\n<p>The following code type checks, but I think I am doing something wrong:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"c1\">-- define x to be 2</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">def</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Nat</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span>\n\n<span class=\"c1\">-- define a proposition that x is equal to 2</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">def</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Prop</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span>\n\n<span class=\"c1\">-- define y to be 3</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">def</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">y</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Nat</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">3</span>\n\n<span class=\"c1\">-- define a proposition that y is equal to x + 1</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">def</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">q</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Prop</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">y</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span>\n\n<span class=\"c1\">-- proof that the proposition (x = 2) is True</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">example</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Eq</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">refl</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">_</span>\n\n<span class=\"c1\">-- given a proof that (x = 2) is True, return a proof that (y = x + 1) is True</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">theorem</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">t</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">q</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"k\">fun</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">hp</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=&gt;</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">match</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">hp</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">with</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"c1\">-- proof of hp using refl</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"c1\">-- assuming _ matches x in the proof below,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"c1\">-- return proof of y = x + 1</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"bp\">|</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Eq</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">refl</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">_</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Eq</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">refl</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">Nat</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">succ</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">_</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>The reason I am suspicious is that the above type checks even when I replace <code>| Eq.refl _ =&gt; Eq.refl (Nat.succ _)</code> with <code>| Eq.refl _ =&gt; Eq.refl _</code><br>\nCan someone help me understand what I am doing wrong here? What would be a correct way to prove that <code>p -&gt; q</code> in this specific case?</p>",
        "id": 479108007,
        "sender_full_name": "Krishna Padmasola",
        "timestamp": 1730009405
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In this case <code>q</code> is unconditionally true, so one can just do <code>fun _ =&gt; rfl</code></p>",
        "id": 479110775,
        "sender_full_name": "Daniel Weber",
        "timestamp": 1730012513
    },
    {
        "content": "<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">theorem</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">t</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">q</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">fun</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">_</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">rfl</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>In this case it's definitionally true, you can just prove it by computation with <code>rfl</code>. A \"more explicit\" proof might be</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">example</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">q</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">simp</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">only</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">q</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">y</span><span class=\"o\">]</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">intro</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">hp</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">rw</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">hp</span><span class=\"o\">]</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">done</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>There's still a large amount of complexity being hidden by the elaborator here even though the procedure is perhaps a bit more explicit, but that's kind of the point of a proof assistant.</p>",
        "id": 479110939,
        "sender_full_name": "Chris Bailey",
        "timestamp": 1730012672
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Fwiw the substitution part is done using the recursor for the Eq type, but I would suggest continuing to develop an intuitive sense for how stuff moves around in the vernacular before digging into that.</p>",
        "id": 479111072,
        "sender_full_name": "Chris Bailey",
        "timestamp": 1730012808
